{
  "answer": "In Manusmriti Chapter 1, one *yuga* (or \"age\") of the gods (*devas*)—defined as the total duration of the four *yugas* (Kṛta, Tretā, Dvāpara, and Kali), including their respective twilights (*sandhyās*) before and after—is precisely **12,000 years**.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [p-03b23e](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-03b23e).  \n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [p-a2767c](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-a2767c), [p-85c454](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-85c454), and [p-03b23e](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-03b23e). (These detail the breakdown: 4,800 for Kṛta; 3,600 for Tretā; 2,400 for Dvāpara; 1,200 for Kali.)  \n[^3]: Manusmṛti, [p-0cd1bd](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-0cd1bd). (Confirms the figure in the context of a *manvantara*.)",
